The key insight is that `IsGaloisGroup G K L` implies that `G` is the group of `K`-automorphisms of `L`, and that these automorphisms preserve the valuation structure. Specifically, for any `g ∈ G` and `x ∈ K`, `g(x) = x`, so `g` acts trivially on `K`. For `x ∈ L`, `g(x) = x` if `x ∈ K`, and in general, `g` preserves the valuation.

