The key insight is that the group `G` is a group of automorphisms of `L` over `K`. This means that for any `g ∈ G` and `z ∈ K`, `g(z) = z`. Therefore, if `z ∈ K` and `g ∈ G`, then `g • z = z`. 

Now, if `z ∈ (valuation K).integer`, this means `valuation K z ≤ 1`. Since `valuation L` is an extension of `valuation K` (from `ValuativeExtension K L`), we have `valuation L z = valuation K z`. Therefore, `valuation L z ≤ 1`, which means `z ∈ (valuation L).integer`.

So to prove the invariance, take any `g ∈ G` and `z ∈ (valuation K).integer`. Then `g • z = z` because `g` fixes `K`. Then `z ∈ (valuation L).integer` because `valuation L z = valuation K z ≤ 1`.

